## About this index

This citations index is assembled by scanning the complete English Pragmatics Learning Hub for Autistic Individuals — 27 pragmatic categories with multi-file research depth, the 40-page Pragmatic Manipulation and Self-Protection Sub-Hub, 4 Tier 1 introduction pages, and 3 foundational research documents (DV frameworks, trauma frameworks, autism application) — and extracting every bibliographic entry that appears in a source list, reference section, or footnote.

**Curation.** Every citation is grounded in peer-reviewed research, authoritative organizational sources, or clearly-labeled community knowledge. Where the evidence is weak, the hub says so. Where it is contested, the hub labels it. The manipulation sub-hub additionally applies a five-tier evidence-quality system — [VALIDATED] / [PRELIMINARY] / [EXTRAPOLATED] / [COMMUNITY KNOWLEDGE] / [CONTESTED] — to its life-stakes content.

**Safety-critical citations** in the manipulation sub-hub (Glass et al. 2008 strangulation OR 7.48, Campbell et al. 2003 femicide risk factors, Bograd & Mederos 1999 couples-therapy contraindication, Sullivan & Bybee 1999 advocacy RCT, Cazalis et al. 2022 autistic women sexual violence prevalence, Hirvikoski et al. 2016 premature mortality gap, Douglas & Sedgewick 2024 weaponized features, Lim Young & Brewer 2022 credibility discount) have been independently verified against primary sources during two separate validation passes.

**Double-empathy framing.** Milton (2012) is cited in every research-autism file and in all four Tier 1 introduction pages. The double empathy problem — that communication breakdowns between autistic and non-autistic people are bidirectional mismatches, not one-sided autistic failures — is the default theoretical stance across the project.

---

*This index is maintained alongside the knowledge base. Additions to any research file should also be reflected here. The authoritative source for each citation is the research file in which it appears — the research file carries the direct link to the external source.*
